<ab><lb n="1"/> <w lemma="ὁ">ἡ</w> <w lemma="πατρίς">πατρίς</w> <lb n="2"/> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Τιβέριος">Τιβέριον</name> <lb n="3"/> <name nymRef="#Κλαύδιος">Κλαύδιον</name> <lb n="4"/> <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Τιβέριος">Τιβερίου</name> <lb n="5"/><name nymRef="#Κλαύδιος"><supplied reason="lost">Κ</supplied>λαυδίου</name>  <lb n="6"/><name nymRef="#Σμάραγδος"><supplied reason="lost">Σ</supplied>μαράγδου</name></persName>  <lb n="7"/><w lemma="υἱός"><supplied reason="lost">υἱ</supplied>ὸν</w>  <name nymRef="#Καπιτωλῖνος">Καπι<lb n="8" break="no"/>τωλεῖνον</name></persName>  </ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p> The fatherland <supplied reason="subaudible">set up a statue of</supplied> Tiberius Claudius Kapitoleinos son of Tiberius Claudius Smaragdos.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The only other Smaragdos attested so far is P. Aelius Claudius Smaragdos, <ref type="inscription" n="1353" target="020308.xml"/> (=67.554).</p>
            <p>Ti. Cl. Kapitoleinos may very well be the very epimelete of two statues of Cl. Antonia Tatiana, <ref type="inscription" n="1793" target="120323.xml"/>, (=LBW 1597), <ref type="inscription" n="1723" target="020013.xml"/> (= 64.427), and the father of Ti. Aur. Cl. Ktesias, honoured in an inscription which might be the pair of this one <ref type="inscription" n="1794" target="120324.xml"/> =(LBW 1598).</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography" n="none">
            <p>Unpublished.</p>
         </div>
